<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between simple and compound interest?", answer: "Simple interest is calculated only on the original principal amount using the formula I = P x r x t. Compound interest is calculated on the principal plus all previously accumulated interest, using the formula A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt). Over time, compound interest generates significantly more growth because you earn interest on your interest, creating an exponential growth curve rather than a linear one." },
  { question: "How much more do you earn with compound interest?", answer: "The difference grows dramatically over time. For example, $10,000 at 5% for 10 years earns $5,000 with simple interest but about $6,289 with annual compounding — 26% more. Over 30 years, simple interest earns $15,000 while compound interest earns roughly $33,219 — more than double. The longer the time period and the higher the rate, the larger the gap becomes." },
  { question: "Where is simple interest used in real life?", answer: "Simple interest is most commonly used for short-term loans, car loans, some personal loans, and certain types of bonds. It is also used in some savings certificates and as a basis for calculating interest charges on credit card balances (though credit cards often compound daily). Simple interest is straightforward to calculate and easier to understand, which is why it appears in simpler financial products." },
  { question: "Where is compound interest used in real life?", answer: "Compound interest applies to most savings accounts, certificates of deposit (CDs), money market accounts, and investment returns. Mortgages, credit cards, and student loans also use compound interest, which works against borrowers. Retirement accounts like 401(k)s and IRAs benefit enormously from compound interest over decades of growth." },
  { question: "Is compound interest always better than simple interest?", answer: "For savers and investors, compound interest is always better because it generates more growth. For borrowers, simple interest is preferable because you pay less in total interest charges. When comparing loan offers, a simple interest loan costs less than a compound interest loan with the same rate and term. When comparing savings products, always look for compound interest with the highest compounding frequency available." }
]) %>

