              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">$34,813 interest (monthly compounding)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Common Uses</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Car loans, some personal loans, bonds</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Savings accounts, CDs, investments, mortgages</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>When Simple Interest Applies</h2>
      <p>
        Simple interest is used in several common financial products. Auto loans typically calculate interest on the original loan balance, making them straightforward to understand and predict. Some personal loans and short-term lending products also use simple interest. Certain government bonds and treasury bills use simple interest calculations. For borrowers, simple interest is advantageous because you pay less total interest compared to an equivalent compound interest loan. The formula I = P x r x t makes it easy to calculate exactly how much you will owe. If you are comparing loan offers, a simple interest loan with the same rate as a compound interest loan will always cost less over the same term.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>When Compound Interest Applies</h2>
      <p>
        Compound interest is the dominant force in the financial world and applies to most savings and investment products. Bank savings accounts, certificates of deposit, money market accounts, and retirement accounts all use compound interest. When you invest in the stock market, your returns compound as reinvested dividends and capital gains generate their own returns. On the borrowing side, mortgages, credit cards, and student loans also use compound interest, which is why debt can grow so quickly when left unpaid. The frequency of compounding matters — daily compounding produces slightly more growth than monthly, which produces more than annual compounding. Most modern savings accounts compound daily, maximizing the benefit to savers.
      </p>

      <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>
        The difference between simple and compound interest is the difference between linear and exponential growth. Over short periods, the gap is modest. Over decades, compound interest generates dramatically more wealth — or dramatically more debt. As a saver, always seek compound interest with the highest frequency available. As a borrower, prefer simple interest loans when possible, and pay down compound interest debt aggressively. The most powerful application of compound interest is long-term investing: starting early and letting your money compound for 30-40 years can turn modest savings into substantial wealth. Use the calculators above with your own numbers to see the impact firsthand.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the difference between simple and compound interest?</h3>
      <p>
        Simple interest is calculated only on the original principal amount using the formula I = P x r x t. Compound interest is calculated on the principal plus all previously accumulated interest, using the formula A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt). Over time, compound interest generates significantly more growth because you earn interest on your interest, creating an exponential growth curve rather than a linear one.
      </p>

      <h3>How much more do you earn with compound interest?</h3>
      <p>
        The difference grows dramatically over time. For example, $10,000 at 5% for 10 years earns $5,000 with simple interest but about $6,289 with annual compounding — 26% more. Over 30 years, simple interest earns $15,000 while compound interest earns roughly $33,219 — more than double. The longer the time period and the higher the rate, the larger the gap becomes.
      </p>

      <h3>Where is simple interest used in real life?</h3>
      <p>
        Simple interest is most commonly used for short-term loans, car loans, some personal loans, and certain types of bonds. It is also used in some savings certificates and as a basis for calculating interest charges on credit card balances (though credit cards often compound daily). Simple interest is straightforward to calculate and easier to understand, which is why it appears in simpler financial products.
      </p>

      <h3>Where is compound interest used in real life?</h3>
      <p>
        Compound interest applies to most savings accounts, certificates of deposit (CDs), money market accounts, and investment returns. Mortgages, credit cards, and student loans also use compound interest, which works against borrowers. Retirement accounts like 401(k)s and IRAs benefit enormously from compound interest over decades of growth.
      </p>

      <h3>Is compound interest always better than simple interest?</h3>
      <p>
        For savers and investors, compound interest is always better because it generates more growth. For borrowers, simple interest is preferable because you pay less in total interest charges. When comparing loan offers, a simple interest loan costs less than a compound interest loan with the same rate and term. When comparing savings products, always look for compound interest with the highest compounding frequency available.
      </p>

